where $\epsilon_{0}$ stands for the phonon energy in the absence of magnetic field, $\lambda$ is the electron-phonon coupling parameter, and $T_{k}=v_{f}\sqrt{2e\hbar B} \left( \sqrt{k} + \sqrt{k+1} \right)$ describes the energy of interband LL transitions, with index $k$, for $\left| n \right| - \left| m \right| = 1$, in which $n$ and $m$ are labels for the initial and final Landau levels involved in the transition. $\delta_k$ represents the LL broadening parameter, which is of particular significance to the present work. The real and complex parts of $\widetilde{\epsilon}=\epsilon-\imath \Gamma$ yield the phonon energy and broadening from the electron-phonon coupling, respectively. Comparison between Eq. \ref{eq1} and the $E_{2g}$ phonon energy and linewidth experimentally obtained as a function of magnetic field allows one to extract sample-related parameters such as $v_F$, $\lambda$ and $\delta_k$.


