We proceed to the investigation of single-layer exfoliated graphene deposited on SiO$_2$. Figure \ref{SLG}(a) shows the optical image of this sample. Figure \ref{SLG}(b) shows the overall Raman spectrum at room temperature with the characteristic $G$ and $2D$ bands and no sign of the defect-activated $D$-band. This result indicates absence of a significant level of structural defects such as atomic vacancies or impurities. A combined analysis of the peak intensities \cite{Das}, areas \cite{Basko}, positions and linewidths \cite{Das,Pisana} of the $G$- and $2D$- bands extracted from the room-temperature Raman spectrum reveals an electrically neutral graphene within our resolution ($n_0=0 \pm 1 \times 10^{12}$ cm$^{-2}$). The $G$-band Raman spectrum for selected magnetic fields and $T=5$ K is displayed in Fig. \ref{SLG}(c). This band clearly splits in two peaks above $\sim 12$ T, in line with previous reports \cite{kim2013filling,Remi}. Figure \ref{SLGB} shows the position of the $G$-band at 5 K as a function of magnetic field. For $B \lesssim 12$ T, where a single $G$-band was observed within our resolution, no magnetophonon resonance could be detected, in contrast to the multilayer epitaxial sample. For $B>12$ T, one of the components of the splitted $G-$band remain at a nearly constant energy position, while a second component follows a pre-resonant behavior associated with the $k=1$ ($n=0 \leftrightarrow \pm 1$) inter-Landau level transitions at $B_{res}^{k=1}=25-30$ T \cite{kim2013filling}. Note that the peak position of this field-dependent component follows a similar behavior found for the multilayer epitaxial graphene in the higher-field regime above 12 T (see also Fig. \ref{MEG}(c)). It is therefore evident from our results and from the literature \cite{kim2013filling,Remi} that single layer graphene on SiO$_2$ is inhomogeneous and regions with two distinct behavious are found within probed areas of a few $\mu$m$^{2}$: (i) regions showing no observable magnetophonon resonance at all and (ii) regions showing clear manifestations of the main $k=0$ resonance.

\begin{figure}
	\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{SLG-sim.eps}	
\caption{\label{SLGB} $G-$band central positions for the single layer graphene sample, obtained by fits using a single lorentzian below 12 T and two lorentzians above 12 T (see also Fig. \ref{SLG}(c)). The grey area marks an intemediate field region where a single peak was employed in the fit although a double peak structure, not resolved in our data, is likely to be present. Circles and triangles refer to datasets taken on two independent runs. The results for the $B$-dependent component above 12 T are given as open symbols. Dashed green and dotted blue lines are the simulated magnetophonon resonance effect according to Eq. \ref*{eq1} using fixed Landau level broadening parameters $\delta=13.6$ and 63 meV, respectively. The inset shows the $B-$dependence of the full width at half maxima for the two peaks observed above 12 T (symbols). The solid red lines in the main panel and in the inset are the results of a simulation using Eq. \ref*{eq1} with $\delta$ parameter dependent on $B$  using $\Delta B=1.7$~T and $\Delta v_F/v_F=0.032$ (see text).}
\end{figure}

Insight into the observed behavior of the $G$-band with field for single-layer exfoliated graphene on SiO$_2$ is gained by an analysis of Eq. \ref{eq1} as a function of the $\delta_k$ parameters related to the LL transition widths. The dashed and dotted lines in Fig. \ref{SLGB} show the calculated $B$-dependence of the $G$-band central wavenumber for two selected values of $\delta$, assumed so far to be the same for all transition indexes $k$. In these simulations, the parameters $\epsilon_0=1582\:$~cm$^{-1}$, $v_{f}=1.15\times10^{6}\:$m/s, $\lambda=5.5\times10^{-3}$ were employed. For $\delta=13.6$ meV, the high-field pre-resonant behavior observed for one of the $G-$band components is captured. However, if the same 
$\delta$ is used for the other LL transitions, the resonance at 3.8 T associated to the $n=-1 \rightarrow 2$ and $n=-2 \rightarrow 1$ LL transitions remains proeminent and would be clearly visible within our resolution. If, on the other hand, a much larger $\delta=63$ meV is employed in the simulations, all the magnetophonon resonances are washed out, including the observed pre-resonant behavior in the field range $B>$12 T. We conclude that, while the $B-$independent component of the $G-$band observed in single-layer graphene on SiO$_2$ may be attributed to sample regions showing a very large $\delta$ value, the behavior observed for the $B-$dependent $G-$band component cannot be explained by single-$\delta$ magnetophonon resonances. In fact, a much larger $\delta_k$ for the low-field resonances ($k \geq 2$) with respect to the main one ($k=$1) is necessary for Eq. \ref*{eq1} to capture the observed behavior of the $B-$dependent $G$-band component of our single-layer graphene sample. This conclusion is not restricted to our exfoliated single-layer sample on SiO$_2$. In fact, recent results of magnetophonon resonance on single-layer graphene encapsuled on hexagonal boron nitride by Neumann {\it et al.} could only be fit with increasing $\delta_k$ parameters with $k$ \cite{neumann2015magneto}.

In the absence of a complete theory that describes the Landau level broadening in neutral graphene, a simple phenomenological model is developed here. The manifestations of MPR in the Raman spectra occur at fields ($B_{res}^k$) where the interband LL energy difference, $E_{res}^k=v_{F}\sqrt{2e\hbar B_{res}^k}(\sqrt{|n|}+ \sqrt{|n+1|})$, equals the $G-$band energy, $E_{G-band}$. From this equation, two possible broadening pathways are readily identified: (i) broadening due to Fermi velocity dispersion, leading to $\delta_k/E_{G-band} = \Delta v_F / v_F$, and (ii) broadening due to strain-induced internal pseudo-magnetic field distribution ~\cite{Castro Neto,andoanomaly,PhysRevLett.97.196804}, leading to  $\delta_k/E_{G-band} = \Delta B / 2 B_{res}^k$. While pathway (i) leads to a single broadening parameter $\delta$ which is independent of the $k$ transition index such as observed for MEG, pathway (ii) leads to $\delta_k$ values inversely proportional to $B_{res}^k$. 

In order to verify broadening mechanisms indicated above are consistent with our observations in SLG, simulations of the $E_{2g}$ phonon energy and linewidth according to Eq. \ref{eq1} were performed considering the Lorentzian-convoluted parameter $\delta_k = (\Delta v_F /v_F + \Delta B / 2 B_{res}^k) E_{G-band}$. Good match with experimental data for the $B-$dependent component of the $G$-band is found using the parameters $\Delta v_F / v_F = 0.032$ and $\Delta B = 1.7$ T (solid lines in Fig. \ref{SLGB} and inset). These parameters indicate that the LL broadening that damps the resonances at low fields in single layer graphene arises mostly from a large local pseudo-magnetic field distribution~\cite{Castro Neto,andoanomaly,PhysRevLett.97.196804}. Indeed, it is known that such pseudo-magnetic fields could reach values up to tens of tesla in some cases ~\cite{Yeh20111649}, therefore the observed value of $\Delta B = 1.7$ T for our single layer graphene sample on SiO$_2$ is a reasonable result. 

For the multilayer epitaxial graphene sample, the strain-induced broadening discussed above for single layer graphene is not relevant, due to the large number of graphene sheets protected by the neighboring layers, and the LL broadening parameter $\delta = 17.6$ meV is independent of $B_{res}^k$. This is characteristic of a broadening mechanism due to Fermi-velocity distribution with $\Delta v_F/ v_F = 0.09$. It is well established that $v_F$ is strongly dependent of a residual interaction with the substrate or neighboring graphene layers, reaching maximum values for suspended single-layer graphene samples ~\cite{Hwang}. We conclude that the residual interlayer interaction in multilayer epitaxial graphene samples fluctuates from layer to layer, leading to a larger Fermi-velocity distribution for such type of graphene samples as compared to single layer graphene.

In summary, a quantitative analysis of the magneto-phonon resonances in multilayer epitaxial and single layer graphene samples allowed us to identify the main Landau level broadening mechanisms for each sample. In single layer graphene, the Landau Levels in the low-field regime broadens mostly due to inhomogeneous strain caused by the interaction with the substrate, while in multilayer epitaxial graphene the Landau Level broadening is caused mainly by variations in the Fermi velocity created by the fluctuations in the interlayer residual interactions. This work paves the way for systematical investigations of Landau level broadening channels for graphene using Raman spectroscopy, which is necessary to optimize sample production methods and bring its unique quantum effects to the subtesla field region.

\section{Methods}
{\bf Sample production} The multilayer epitaxial sample was obtained by decomposition of the carbon face of 4H-SiC$(000\overline{1})$ substrate in argon atmosphere. Sublimation time was 60 minutes at $T = 2048$ K. Further details on the preparation and characterization of this sample by Raman scattering, atomic force microscopy and grazing-incidence x-ray diffraction are given in Ref. \cite{mendes2012}. The single layer graphene flake was produced by conventional mechanical exfoliation of natural graphene deposited over the $300$~nm SiO$_2$ layer of a Si substrate.

{\bf Raman scattering} The micro-Raman spectra were performed using a $488$ nm Ar-ion laser and a $15$~T magnetocryostat. The sample was fixed to piezoelectric stages. The sample, $xyz$ stages and objective were immersed in He gas or superfluid. The magnetic field was perpendicular to the sample surface. The elastic component of the scattered signal was rejected by an edge filter. For the experiment on multilayer epitaxial graphene on SiC, a $200$~$\mu$m diameter size optical fiber, which works as a confocal configuration, was used to transport the Raman signal to the entrance of a single $1800$~g/mm grating spectrometer coupled with a liquid nitrogen-cooled charge coupled device detector; the laser was focused using a 50X objective lens, with 7 mm working distance and a spot size of $\approx2.5$~$\mu$m. For single layer graphene on SiO$_2$, a single $1200$~g/mm grating spectrometer with a peltier-cooled CCD detector was employed; we used a $40\times$ objective lens with a $200$~$\mu$m working distance, resulting in $\sim 3.5$~$\mu$m focal spot diameter.


