\begin{abstract}

The singular half-integer quantum hall effect in graphene is a direct consequence of the characteristic Landau levels (LL) predicted by the Dirac equation. Albeit sharp levels are required to reinforce the manifestation of this effect, little information on the most relevant mechanisms leading to broadening of quantized electronic levels in graphene samples is presently available. In this work, micro-Raman experiments at low temperatures and fields up to 15 T were performed on two electrically neutral graphene samples, namely a natural single-layer graphene flake deposited over a Si/SiO$_2$ substrate and a multilayer epitaxial graphene sample produced by silicon sublimation out of a SiC surface. Interband LL transition widths were extracted by the damping of the magnetophonon resonances associated with optically active LL transitions crossing the energy of the $E_{2g}$ Raman-active phonon. The dependence of the transition widths with the resonance fields provides direct information on the broadening mechanisms. From this analysis, the LL broadening in multilayer epitaxial graphene on SiC is attributed to a distribution of Fermi velocities due to fluctuations of residual interlayer graphene interactions, while an additional mechanism due to the presence of random strain-induced pseudomagnetic fields takes place in single layer graphene on SiO$_2$. This work demonstrates the existence of distinct mechanisms that degrate the quantum electronic effects in graphene, which are affected differently by the sample production methodology.

\end{abstract}



\maketitle


The Landau Level (LL) energies for the linear electronic bands around the Dirac points in graphene are $E_{n}= sgn (n)v_{F}\sqrt{2e\hbar B |n|}$ ~\cite{Castro Neto}, where the index $n=0$, $\pm 1$, $\pm2$, ..., $v_F$ is the Fermi velocity and $B$ is the magnetic field perpendicular to the carbon sheet. Ideal graphene, i.e., a perfectly flat, isolated, defect-free and strain-free layer, is expected to show extremely sharp LL at low temperatures. On the other hand, real samples show imperfections that are characteristic of the sample production method, leading to LL broadening and consequent damping of the effects associated to the Dirac equation. A proper understanding of the main mechanisms of LL broadening is therefore desirable and should help in the quest for optimized graphene samples with reinforced quantum relativistic effects.

As detailed below, the mechanisms of LL broadening may be pinned down by a quantitative analysis of the {\it B}-dependence of the LL width. Such information can be achieved  by direct observations of the LL by Scanning Tunelling Spectroscopy \cite{Li_STS,Mayer_STS}, Infrared absorption \cite{SadowskiIR,JiangIR,OrlitaIR} and Raman scattering \cite{PhysRevLett.107.036807,FaugerasEPL}. Alternatively, the broadening of LL may be more conveniently studied by an analysis of phonon Raman scattering, which is a versatile and widespread technique that probe structural and electronic properties of graphitic samples. In fact, electron-phonon interaction in graphene leads to magneto-phonon resonances (MPR) when the energy of an optically active LL transition obeying $|n|-|m|=1$ crosses the energy of the $E_{2g}$ Raman-active phonon \cite{ando2005electronic,tando,Goerbig}, causing oscillations of the phonon energy and linewidth. Several works have reported the MPR from Dirac fermions in graphene and graphitic samples \cite{PhysRevLett.107.036807,faugerasfit,PhysRevLett.105.227401,PhysRevB.85.121403,Goler20121289,kim2013filling,leszczynski2014electrical,neumann2015magneto}. For electrically neutral graphene, the MPR are described by  \cite{faugerasfit}
